OUR PRINCIPLES
English version

Miyuki is a software project created by a diverse community of educators from
Argentina, formed within the framework of the public university system. Our aim
is to provide a tool for learning programming, using open content and without
requiring Internet access.

To achieve this, we use free and open-source software components from the Mumuki
platform (https://github.com/mumuki/) and its Creative Commons-licensed content
(https://github.com/mumukiproject/), to which we have added tools to simplify
installation and reduce dependence on a client-server architecture.

While these goals are primarily pragmatic (reducing server maintenance costs,
enabling use even with low-quality or no Internet connections) and respond to
real and everyday problems, they also have deeper roots.

We believe that the software we build and use is not neutral [1]; on the
contrary, every line of code is political: it is created within a social,
historical, and cultural context. Everything we program is shaped by that
context, but it also has the potential to transform it. Through action or
omission, software will always be a vehicle to express, reproduce, reinforce, or
challenge political visions.

Within this framework, we who develop Miyuki acknowledge the existence of
systems of oppression. In particular, though not exclusively: the world is
shaped by power relations that harm people based on race, gender, sexual
orientation, social conditions, disabilities, and nationality. Every time our
code does not challenge these systems of oppression [2], we are accepting and
perpetuating them.

For these reasons, the Miyuki team declares:

  * our commitment to continuously observe these injustices and to include, as
    an essential part of the development process, critical analysis of the
    impact of our work on these systems of oppression.

  * our hope that those who use the application, as people learning to program
    and build software, will pursue a humanistic and holistic education that
    goes beyond technical issues and embraces the transformative potential of
    their work in the pursuit of a more just world [3].

